1 Intro

1.1 Context

One of the goals of sepages was to analyse the link between exposure to endocrine disruptors during pregnancy and the infant’s neurological development. One of the experiments to quantify neurologic development was to perform eye tracking experiments at Grenoble’s LPNC BabyLab. Sepages infants were subject to several tasks and were seen up to 3 times: at 6 months, 12 months, 24 months.

Here are the first descriptive stats on the babylab dataset babylab_190502.dta.

First we present the number of infants, observations and some of their characteristics.

Then we present information on the different scores provided by the experiment. In this dataset we have seven scores for two tasks: scene perception and face perception and recognition.

1.2 Eye tracking

Eye movement is measured by X-Y coordinates continuously. Eye movement consists of a sequence of saccades (movement) and fixations (non movements). Out of this continuous X-Y data many scores are computed mainly measuring saccades and fixations (number, frequency, etc).

These scores are:

  1. n_sacc: Number of saccades during the task
  2. param1: the value of a in v = b*d^a
  3. param2: the value of b in v = b*d^a
  4. corr: the corresponding correlation
  5. n_fix_mean: the mean number of fixation over 5 seconds of presentation
  6. look_t_mean: the mean looking time over 5 seconds of presentation
  7. fix_dur_mean: the mean duration of one fixation

1.3 Tasks

Here we briefly present the two tasks for which data is available.

1.3.1 Scene perception

An image is shown to the baby for five seconds each. The experiment is repeated six times.

We are interested in looking at what part of the iamge the infant looks at.

1.3.2 Face perception and recognition

Two pictures of the same human face are simultaneously shown to the baby for 10 seconds. Then, one picture is replaced by a new one (the faces have different levels of attractiveness) and the two different pictures are shown to the baby for 10 seconds. The experiment is repeated four times.

We are interested in measuring the reaction to novelty: the baby should preferentially look at the new face.

But problem here: the duration of exposure to the different pictures is too long. WHY???

5 Collection ages

Notes on the effect of age from meeting in may 2019:

We should not stratify the analysis on age because few babies for some age groups. If really necessary: normalization, a posteriori, on the residuals. We will start by looking at the effect of age on these measures model for longitudinal data might be an option or focusing only on the 2 years but would be nice to have all the measurements.

Remarks on baby-adult differences: * Babies tend to look at pictures for shorter periods than adults; * Centrality bias stronger for adults than babies (not considered in the following experiments); * Adults always start to look to the left of the picture, whatever it is a motion or a portrait. Babies always start to look to the left of the picture if it is a motion but start from right or left if it is a portrait; * When a moving target must be followed, babies tend to be late while adults may be a bit in advance. ^

Age effect more or less strong according to the kind of pictures. Here, babies are homogeneous: we will quickly notice if a baby does not behave as the others.

6.2.5 Conclusions

Scores that seem to be positively correlated:

  • Mean looking time and mean number of fixations within each tasks
  • All other scores between tasks (eg mean fixation duration for task 1 and for task 2)

Scores that seem to be negatively correlated:

  • param1 and param2 within each task
